The **logistic regression** algorithm searches for a function $$ P: [0,3] \to [0,1]$$ If $x = $ petal width, $P(x)$ is an estimate (= a guess) of the probability that the plant is a virginica.

  • P(x)>0.5 answer yes (the plant is a virginica)
  • P(x)$\leq$ 0.5 answer no

The idea of logistic regression is to look for a function depending on paramters $W$ and $B$:

$$P_{W,B}(x) = \sigma(Wx+B)$$ where $$\sigma : \mathbb{R} \to [0,1]$$ is the sigmoid function defined by $$ \sigma(x) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}$$

$$ \sigma : x \mapsto \frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}$$

We call $W$ the weight and $B$ the bias. </font>

In [7]:
def sigmoid(x):
    return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))

Problem: the accuracy is constant on huge zones¶

2.2 The cross entropy loss function¶

Fix the weigth $W$ and bias $B$.


$$\mathcal{L}(p,y) := y \log(p) + (1-y)\log(1-p)$$
$$\text{Loss} :=\sum_{i=1}^n \mathcal{L}(p_i,y_i) = \sum_{i=1}^n y_i \log(p_i) + (1-y_i)\log(1-p_i)$$
where

  • $y_i\in \{0,1\}$ is the class of the i-th sample

  • $p_i \in [0,1]$ is the predicted probability $P_{w,b}(x_i)$ calculated by the logistic regression model for parameter values $w$ and $b$

loss1 = - np.log(probas)

plt.plot(probas,loss1,label='y = 1')

    loss = model.evaluate(iris[['petal_width']], iris[['isVirginica']], \

    return loss
